  "set_overview": {
    "summary": "Secrets of Strixhaven features an environment where white aggro goes under Prismari and Quandrix decks, while Witherbloom plays an awkward middle ground. Converge and splashes can easily be accommodated in non-white strategies, leading to 'Converge soups' full of removal, card draw, and bombs. Removal is highly effective, and games are often defined by the tension between aggressive decks and value-oriented control builds.",
    "color_ranking": [
      "{W} White",
      "{B} Black",
      "{R} Red",
      "{U} Blue",
      "{G} Green"
    ],
    "color_notes": {
      "{W} White": "Strong aggro color. Cards like Elite Interceptor, Ajani's Response, and Stone Docent form the backbone of assertive decks.",
      "{U} Blue": "Supports control and value. Essence Scatter, Run Behind, and Quick Study provide solid answers and card advantage.",
      "{B} Black": "Offers premium removal like Last Gasp and Cost of Brilliance. Often anchors Witherbloom midrange or Silverquill aggro.",
      "{R} Red": "Solid removal like Unsubtle Mockery and Rubble Rouser. Pairs well in aggressive strategies or as removal splash.",
      "{G} Green": "The weakest and most narrow color. Requires specific synergies or multicolor strategies to shine. Studious First-Year and Burrog Barrage are key."
    },
    "key_gameplay_notes": [
      "White aggro vs 'Converge soup' is the defining dynamic of the format.",
      "Removal is essential and highly efficient across most colors.",
      "Card draw is critical to out-scale aggro decks and win 'soup' mirrors.",
      "Splashing is very viable, especially in non-white 'Converge' decks.",
      "Many decks can go under the radar, like pump spell combo, flicker, or artifact synergies."
    ]
  },
